<DOC><DOCNO> AP880826-0081 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 0710EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Colombia-Rebels     08-26 0235</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Colombia-Rebels,0242</SECOND><HEAD>Guerrillas Stage Deadliest Raid In Years; 39 Reported Killed</HEAD><DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   About 300 leftist guerrillas destroyed amilitary base and police headquarters in a village attack thatkilled 39 people, the deadliest raid by guerrillas in severalyears, the Defense Ministry said.   A ministry statement said Thursday that 15 guerrillas, 12civilians, 10 soldiers and two policemen were killed. At least 10civilians and soldiers were wounded and an unknown number weremissing after Wednesday's raid, the communique said.   The Defense Ministry said the rebels from the Maoist People'sLiberation Army and the pro-Soviet Colombian Revolutionary ArmedForces ambushed two security force patrols outside Saisa, a villageof 1,200 residents about 250 miles north of Bogota.   Ten soldiers and two policemen died, the ministry said.   Civilians in Saisa joined 15 soldiers that remained in thevillage to battle the guerrillas for four hours. The battle left 15guerrillas and 12 civilians dead, the statement said.   The statement said civilian victims of the guerrilla attackincluded a woman and her two small children who were burned alive.   The ministry said reinforcements were sent Thursday to the areabut it was not immediately known if there was any new fighting.   The attacks came as armed groups and the government of PresidentVirgilio Barco made moves to begin a new peace process. Guerrillashave been fighting to overthrow Colombia's government for 30 years.</TEXT></DOC>